        <tr> 
          <td height="15">&nbsp;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td><textarea name="textarea" cols="40" rows="30" readonly>Image 401

A page from the York Psalter, produced in the north of England c.1170 in an angular, stylized but vigorous English Romanesque. At the top of the page is an image of Christ appearing to Thomas the Apostle, after his resurrection; the other apostles  and the Virgin Mary (with blue veil at the right of the group)stand by in amazement. Below is an image of Christ walking on water, to the amazement of the Apostles who follow in boat. St Peter is marked out in both images, in the first by carrying keys, and in second it is he who is naked in the water, clutching at the hand of Christ. The episode with Doubting Thomas follows the Resurrection, whereas Christ's walking on the water preceded his Passion, but the non-chronological organization of this page may be intended thematically, to illustrate the lack of faith on the part of some apostles. 

</textarea></td>
